<F P=100> EAST EUROPE </F>
<F P=101> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Agreement Signed With Austria on Radiation Monitoring </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Agreement Signed With Austria on Radiation Monitoring </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2405144594 Prague CTK in English 2032 GMT 23 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2405144594 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, May 23 (CTK) -- Equipment for 
monitoring and exchange of data on radiation between Slovakia 
and Austria will start operating in September, according to an 
agreement signed today. 
  The signatories were Slovak Environment Minister Juraj 
Hrasko 
and Austrian Health Minister Christa Krammer. 
  "Slovakia is the first country with which we will connect 
systems warning against radiation," Krammer said at a press 
conference today. 
  She added that talks are under way also with the Czech 
Republic and Slovenia, and Hungary and Germany are also under 
consideration. The Austrian Government paid 3.5 million 
schillings for the system. 
  The move is an important step on Slovakia's path towards 
joining international cooperation in the area. The Austrian 
monitoring system is composed of 336 automated measuring 
stations, while Slovakia has only 26. 
  The need to connect both systems resulted from a visit of a 
Slovak Government delegation to Austria in May last year. 

</TEXT>

