<H3> <TI>   Pollution From Pig Farms Said To Damage Forests </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Pollution From Pig Farms Said To Damage Forests </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   94WN0293A London THE TIMES in English 12 May 94 p 6--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 94WN0293A </F>
<F P=104>  London THE TIMES </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

  [Text] Airborne pollution from pig farms and other 
intensive agriculture sites is damaging British forests. 
  Scientists have linked ammonia emissions from livestock with 
acidification of forest soils, which causes parts of trees to 
wither and die. 
  The research, carried out by the Institute of Terrestrial 
Ecology's Merlewood Research Station at Grange-over-Sands, 
Cumbria, has drawn attention to a source of pollution that up to 
now has been all but ignored in Britain. 
  Since 1950 there has been a 50 per cent growth in emissions 
of ammonia over Europe and in some countries it may have doubled. 
  Agriculture is believed to account for 95 per cent of these 
emissions and the new research indicates that large tracts of 
British woodland may be suffering as a result. 
  The study, carried out by Dr Phil Ineson with funding from 
the Department of the Environment, concentrated on Scots pine 
and Norway spruce woods near a pig farm at Wensleydale in the 
Yorkshire Dales. 
  Dr Ineson, writing in the Natural Environment Research 
Council's Nerc News, said measurements showed high 
levels of ammonia-linked pollution downwind of the farm and less 
upwind. Concentrations were highest during muck spreading and 
when pigs were moved on to the farm in the winter and spring. 
  TIMES NEWSPAPERS LIMITED, 1994 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

