<H3> <TI>   Farmers Ordered To Cut Nitrate Pollution </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Farmers Ordered To Cut Nitrate Pollution </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   94WN0299A London THE TIMES in English 19 May 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> 94WN0299A </F>
<F P=104>  London THE TIMES </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by Nick Nuttall, environment correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Tough restrictions on farmers were announced 
yesterday by the Government to cut down on pollution from 
nitrates which threatens rivers and wildlife. 
  The environment and agriculture departments unveiled 72 
Vulnerable Zones, covering 1.6 million acres, in which farmers 
will have to modify their use of manure, fertilisers and sludge 
to curb nitrates leaking into rivers and the sea. Many of the 
areas are in East Anglia, where drinking water samples sometimes 
fail European standards. 
  Thirty three areas were also announced where water companies 
will have to fit sewage treatment works with anti-phosphate 
pollution equipment. They cover Windermere and the rivers Avon, 
Test, Blackwater and Nene. 

</TEXT>

